@node "kinstall" "Installation"

 @{b}AmiHunter.amirx Installation@{ub}

  AmiHunter should have been installed by KĻĻ's installation, but I'll tell
  you where things are and go....:)

  AmiHunter.amirx -> AmIRC/Rexx/

  All the required libs in LIBS:

 @{b}AmiHunter.amirx Aliases@{ub}

   The following Aliases are part of the KĻĻ Aliases Plugin.
   Do NOT add them manually!

     Find   = /rx Amihunter find %p   
     Get    = /rx Amihunter get  %p 
     CSend  = /rx AmiHunter Csend %p       
     USend  = /rx Amihunter Usend %p     
     VRead  = /rx Amihunter vread %p
     BSeek  = /rx Amihunter bseek %p
     LSites = /rx AmiHunter lsites %p

 @{b}Configuring@{ub}

  Open KuangEleven GUI and go to Addon page and configure all Amihunter 
  options, and make sure you configure proxy. and Save.

     See @{"How to Use" link "usage"} for Usage......

@endnode

@node "install" "Installation"

 @{b}AmiHunter.amirx Installation@{ub}

  AmiHunter should have been installed by KĻĻ's installation, but I'll tell
  you where things are and go....:)

  AmiHunter.amirx -> AmIRC/Rexx/

  All the required libs in LIBS:

  Libs:rexxkuang11.library v 0.26 or greater
  Libs:rexxdossupport.library
  Libs:rexxreqtools.library
  Libs:rexxsupport.library

 @{b}AmiHunter.amirx Aliases@{ub}

     Add the following Aliases to AmIRC:

     Find   = /rx Amihunter find %p   
     Get    = /rx Amihunter get  %p 
     CSend  = /rx AmiHunter Csend %p       
     USend  = /rx Amihunter Usend %p     
     VRead  = /rx Amihunter vread %p
     BSeek  = /rx Amihunter bseek %p
     LSites = /rx AmiHunter lsites %p

 @{b}Configuring@{ub}

  You must configure AmiHunter by loading it your favorite text editor
  and changing the configuration variables to suit your needs. The
  script (or at least the configuration part ;) is very well commented,
  and should pose no problem even if you do not have knowledge of the
  ARexx language. Note that you MUST configure AmiHunter before you use
  it for the first time, as it is highly unlikely the default config is
  right for you.

     See @{"How to Use" link "usage"} for Usage......



@endnode

@node "usage" "Using AmiHunter"

 @{b}/FIND@{ub} -- Find files on AmiNet

  @{fg shine}Syntax:@{fg text} <search-keyword(s)> [EXACT] [-m=<maxhits>|-c|-t=<nick/channel>]
          [-w=<width>] [-s=<sitenumber>]

@{fg fill}   <search-keyword(s)>@{fg text}

     What to search for. You can specify a space seperated list of keywords
     to search for if you enclose it in double quotes (").

@{fg fill}   [EXACT]@{fg text}

     With this switch AmiHunter will search for the exact phrase you
     specified, instead of searching all entries that contain your keywords
     in random order.

@{fg fill}   -m=<maxhits>@{fg text}

     You can modify the maximum number of search results with this flag.
     It defaults to the amount specified by the maxhits config variable in
     the script.

@{fg fill}   -c@{fg text}

     This makes AmiHunter output the search results to the current channel.
     The maximum number of search results defaults to the amount specified
     by the maxhitspub config variable in the script. This flag replaces
     CSHOW. Cannot be used in conjunction with -t.

@{fg fill}   -t=<nick/channel>@{fg text}

     Makes AmiHunter output the search results to specified target (which
     can be a #channel or a user). This flag replaces RAWSEND, and cannot
     be used with -c.

@{fg fill}   -w=<width>@{fg text}

     Specifies the maximum width of the output. This feature is not
     supported by some AmiNet search engines.

@{fg fill}   -s=<sitenumber>@{fg text}

     Normally AmiHunter uses the default site as defined by the sitenumber
     config variable in the script, but you can override that behaviour by
     using this flag.

   FIND will display any search results, prefixed by a number. This number
   is what is used by the other commands to identify the files.

  @{i}Examples: @{ui}

    /FIND "irc client"        Searches for anything with "irc" AND "client"
    /FIND exact "irc client"  Searches for anything with "irc client" exactly
    /FIND amsd -m=5           Shows 5 lines of output
    /FIND amsd -w=120         Truncates output to 120 characters
    /FIND amsd -w=60 -m=10    Shows up to 10 lines truncating to 60 width
    /FIND "comm/net IRC"      Will search in the comm/net directory for "IRC"
    /FIND amsd -s=4           Will use site number 4 from the site list
    /FIND cool -c             Finds "cool", dumps results to current channel
    /FIND cool -t eNTiTy      Finds "cool", dumps results to user eNTiTy


 @{B}/GET@{UB} -- Download files

  @{fg shine}Syntax:@{fg text} <filenumber(s)> [-s=<sitenumber>] [-d=<downloaddir>]

@{fg fill}   <filenumber(s)>@{fg text}

     Space seperated list of filenumbers to download.

@{fg fill}   -s=<sitenumber>@{fg text}

     See FIND.

@{fg fill}   -d=<downloaddir>@{fg text}

     Download files to this directory.


 @{b}/CSEND@{ub} -- Send selected search results to the channel
                                                                       
  @{fg shine}Syntax:@{fg text} <list of search-result numbers>
                                  
  @{i}Example: @{ui}

    /CSEND 2 3

    (this will send search results no. 2 and 3 to the current channel)


@{b}/USEND@{ub} -- Send selected search results to a user

  @{fg shine}Syntax:@{fg text} <nick|%U> <list of search-result numbers>

@{fg fill}   nick@{fg text}

    The user to send the results to.

@{fg fill}   %U@{fg text}

    The results will be send to the nick selected in the current channel's
    userlist.

@{fg fill}   list of search-result numbers@{fg text}

    The search results to send to the target.

  @{i}Example: @{ui}

    /USEND Bossman^ 2 3

    (will send search results 2 and 3 to someone called Bossman^)
         %U - will get select nick from users list                     
                                                                       

 @{b}/VREAD@{ub} -- View readme of selected search results

  @{fg shine}Syntax:@{fg text} <list of search-result numbers>

  Will download the readme to T: and use multiview (or compatible viewer, see
  AmiHunter.amirx script itself) to read the readme text.


 @{b}/BSEEK@{ub} -- Send search command to browser

  @{fg shine}Syntax:@{fg text} <search keywords>

  This command 'does' an Aminet (aminet.org) search using your browser.


@{b} Notes:@{ub}
                                                                       
 o  If you search for more than one keyword you MUST put it in quotes. 
 o  Quotes must be " quotes, not ' quotes.                             





@endnode

